6.00	Oil_price_increases_of_2004	2000s energy crisis	From the mid-1980s to September 2003, the inflation-adjusted price of a barrel of crude oil on NYMEX was generally under $25/barrel. During 2003, the price rose above $30, reached $60 by 11 August 2005, and peaked at $147.30 in July 2008. Commentators attributed these price increases to many factors, including reports from the United States Department of Energy and others showing a decline in petroleum reserves}}&lt;/ref&gt; Reference not available --&gt;, worries over peak oil, Middle East tension, and oil price speculation.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Price_of_oil_%282003-2008%29.png/220px-Price_of_oil_%282003-2008%29.png
